<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B79C3C38DFBC536BB" blockId="18.[189,1086,706,733]" box="[189,1086,706,733]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Baltic amber is considered to be of Bartonian–Priabonian age, ca 34–38 Ma.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34CD692D10B496B79C3C24BFECA32EC" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B79C3C24BFEB53778" blockId="18.[189,334,772,798]" box="[189,334,772,798]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
<heading id="D0A13275D10B496B79C3C24BFEB53778" bold="true" box="[189,334,772,798]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10B496B79C3C24BFEB53778" bold="true" box="[189,334,772,798]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B7994C27CFEBE372B" blockId="18.[188,1400,819,1091]" box="[234,325,819,845]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10B496B7994C27CFEBE372B" bold="true" box="[234,325,819,845]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Female</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B79C3C219FE733025" blockId="18.[188,1400,819,1091]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
BODY. BL = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B782EC21AFE473716" box="[336,444,853,880]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.52" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="3.52">3.52 mm</quantity>
. Head glabrous, smooth, as high as long (HeL = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7A86C21AFB9E3716" box="[1016,1125,853,880]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.50 mm</quantity>
); eye round, small, less than a third of head length (ED = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7B41C236FD5037F5" box="[575,683,889,915]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7999999999999998" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="0.18">0.18 mm</quantity>
); frontal prominence elongate; toruli facing upwards; antenna slightly but homogeneously pubescent; scape longer than head length; pedicel conical, thinner at base; F1 second longest; F2–F12 of subequal length, gradually widening; F12 as long as wide; F13 widest and longest, conical (antennomeres length, in mm: Sc- 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7A45C2ADFC5C379B" box="[827,935,994,1021]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="0.58">0.58 mm</quantity>
; P-0.11; F1-0.17; F2-0.10; F3-0.10; F4- 0.11; F5-0.11; F6-0.11; F7-0.12; F8-0.11; F9-0.11; F10-0.11; F11-0.11; F12-0.12; F13-0.21); mandibles of ordinary form.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B79C3C524FE5C3131" blockId="18.[189,1399,1130,1367]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
MESOSOMA. Shorter than metasoma (MsL = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7BB7C525FCC230E3" box="[713,825,1130,1157]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.10 mm</quantity>
); pronotum not elongate, with straight posterior margin, epomia absent; mesoscutum convex, with notauli deep and complete; anterior scutellar pit large, rounded; scutellum sub-quadrate, without posterior scutellar pits; propodeum dorsally with prominent plicae, median keel simple. Fore wing very reduced, hardly reaching posterior margin of petiole (FwL = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B780AC5B8FE183174" box="[372,483,1271,1298]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.04" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="1.04">1.04 mm</quantity>
). Hind wing reduced, shorter than fore wing (HwL = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7D26C5B8FB3D3174" box="[1112,1222,1271,1298]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="0.52">0.52 mm</quantity>
). Legs slender, with only hind coxa widened; erect setae along hind tibia and tarsomere; tibial spur formula 1-2-2; tarsal claws simple.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B79C3C430FE7D3240" blockId="18.[189,1401,1407,1574]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
METASOMA. Petiole 1.3 times as long as wide (PtL = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7A56C430FC6F31FF" box="[808,916,1407,1433]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="0.28">0.28 mm</quantity>
; PtW = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7A8BC430FB9931FF" box="[1013,1122,1407,1433]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="0.22">0.22 mm</quantity>
), longitudinally ribbed; gaster fusiform and elongate (GL = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7B11C4EDFD2631DB" box="[623,733,1442,1469]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.64" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="1.64">1.64 mm</quantity>
; GH = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7A47C4EDFC5231DB" box="[825,937,1442,1469]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8999999999999995" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="0.59">0.59 mm</quantity>
); S2 and T2 longest, covering anterior half of gaster; T2 striated medially at junction with petiole; three ring-like segments visible posteriorly to large tergite; apical sternites fused into long, smooth triangle; ovipositor exerted, shorter than gaster (OL = 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7872C743FE813240" box="[268,378,1548,1574]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.4" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="0.74">0.74 mm</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B7994C702FED13201" blockId="18.[189,305,1613,1674]" box="[234,298,1613,1639]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10B496B7994C702FED13201" bold="true" box="[234,298,1613,1639]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B79C3C73FFECA32EC" blockId="18.[189,305,1613,1674]" box="[189,305,1648,1674]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Unknown</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34CD692D10B496A79C3C7FDFC233673" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" type="discussion">
<subSubSection id="C34CD692D10B496A79C3C7FDFACA35D6" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B79C3C7FDFEBF32AA" blockId="18.[189,324,1714,1740]" box="[189,324,1714,1740]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
<heading id="D0A13275D10B496B79C3C7FDFEBF32AA" bold="true" box="[189,324,1714,1740]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10B496B79C3C7FDFEBF32AA" bold="true" box="[189,324,1714,1740]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Comments</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10B496B79C3C7AFFB5433E1" blockId="18.[188,1399,1760,1928]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
The specimen was originally identified as the extant species 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10B496B7AF8C7AFFAAA329D" authority="(Thomson, 1858)" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Thomson" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[902,1361,1760,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrocera">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10B496B7AF8C7AFFB85329C" box="[902,1150,1760,1786]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Pantolyta macrocera</emphasis>
(Thomson, 1858)
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC7F8E8D10B496B79C3C64CFEB53378" author="Buhl P. N." box="[189,334,1795,1822]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" pagination="57 - 61" refId="ref14115" refString="Buhl P. N. 2002. On a Baltic amber collection of Platygastridae and Diapriidae (Hymenoptera). Entomologiske Meddelelser 70: 57 - 61." type="journal article" year="2002">Buhl (2002)</bibRefCitation>
because of the brachypterous morph. However, we can observe some differences on the petiole and gaster. 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10B496B78DDC668FD903327" authority="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen, 2022" authorityName="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2022" box="[419,619,1831,1857]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10B496B78DDC668FD903327" box="[419,619,1831,1857]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Pantolyta similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A211E470D10B496B7B0CC668FD343327" box="[626,719,1831,1857]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
displays numerous fine longitudinal ribs dorsally on the petiole whereas there are fewer ribs in 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10B496B7B05C604FCEF3302" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Thomson" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[635,788,1867,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrocera">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10B496B7B05C604FCEF3302" box="[635,788,1867,1892]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">P. macrocera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Additionally, 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10B496B7AC0C604FBA33302" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Thomson" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[958,1112,1867,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrocera">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10B496B7AC0C604FBA33302" box="[958,1112,1867,1892]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">P. macrocera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has shorter and stronger medial striations on T2 than 
<emphasis id="B922590BD10B496B7B73C622FD2833E1" box="[525,723,1901,1927]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
Pantolyla 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10B496B7BF8C622FD2833E1" authorityName="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2022" box="[646,723,1901,1927]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">similis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC7F8E8D10B496B7B9CC622FBC133E1" author="Chemyreva V. G. &amp; Kolyada V. A." box="[738,1082,1901,1927]" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" pagination="137 - 162" refId="ref14407" refString="Chemyreva V. G. &amp; Kolyada V. A. 2021. Taxonomy of the genera Acropiesta, Anommatium, Erasikea and Pantolyta (Diapriidae: Belytinae) with review of species occurring in Russia. Zoosystemica Rossica 30: 137 - 162. https: // doi. org / 10.31610 / zsr / 2021.30.1.137" type="journal article" year="2021">Chemyreva &amp; Kolyada 2021</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 
<quantity id="4CAE28FCD10B496B7D0DC622FB5933E1" box="[1139,1186,1901,1927]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.1" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" unit="g" value="11.0">11g</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10A496A79C3C046FACA35D6" blockId="19.[188,1399,265,432]" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">
Among the Baltic amber species, it differs from other 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10A496A7A24C046FBD63545" box="[858,1069,265,291]" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10A496A7A24C046FC373545" box="[858,972,265,291]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">Pantolyta</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
as follows: 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10A496A7DB9C045FABA3545" authorityName="Buhl" authorityYear="1999" box="[1223,1345,266,291]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antiqua">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10A496A7DB9C045FABA3545" box="[1223,1345,266,291]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">P. antiqua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10A496A79C3C062FE9E3520" authorityName="Maneval" authorityYear="1938" box="[189,357,300,326]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="somnulenta">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10A496A79C3C062FE9E3520" box="[189,357,300,326]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">P. somnulenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are macropterous and have a shorter petiole; 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10A496A7AE3C063FB513520" authority="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen, 2022" authorityName="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2022" box="[925,1194,300,326]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="augustinusii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10A496A7AE3C063FB513520" box="[925,1194,300,326]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">Pantolyta augustinusii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A211E470D10A496A7DC8C062FAEE3521" box="[1206,1301,301,327]" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has the epomia present, whereas it is absent in 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10A496A7BFAC000FCB1350F" authority="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen, 2022" authorityName="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2022" box="[644,842,335,361]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10A496A7BFAC000FCB1350F" box="[644,842,335,361]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">Pantolyta similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A211E470D10A496A7A2FC01FFC55350C" box="[849,942,336,362]" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
; 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10A496A7AC7C000FB46350F" authority="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen, 2022" authorityName="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2022" box="[953,1213,335,361]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chemyrevae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10A496A7AC7C000FB46350F" box="[953,1213,335,361]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">Pantolyta chemyrevae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A211E470D10A496A7DBAC01FFAE5350C" box="[1220,1310,336,362]" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has the epomia present, the anterior scutellar pit more quadrate, the petiole more elongate and the striations on T2 shorter; 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10A496A7838C0D8FE4335D6" authorityName="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Buhl" baseAuthorityYear="2002" box="[326,440,407,432]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janzeni">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10A496A7838C0D8FE4335D6" box="[326,440,407,432]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">P. janzeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C56FE9AD10A496A788EC0D8FD7935D6" authorityName="Brazidec &amp; Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Jouault &amp; Nel" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[496,642,406,432]" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Pantolyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perrichoti">
<emphasis id="B922590BD10A496A788EC0D8FD7935D6" box="[496,642,406,432]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">P. perrichoti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a longer petiole, more than two times as long as wide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<paragraph id="8BE98519D10A496A7B3BC098FC143597" blockId="19.[581,1007,471,533]" box="[581,1007,471,497]" pageId="19" pageNumber="76">
Subfamily 
